    content: `
## Municipal Bonds vs Corporate Bonds: The Tax Calculation

The key formula: **Tax-Equivalent Yield = Muni Yield ÷ (1 − Your Marginal Tax Rate)**

**Example:** 3.5% muni bond, 32% federal + 5% state = 37% combined marginal rate.
Tax-equivalent yield = 3.5% ÷ (1 − 0.37) = **5.56%**

If corporate bonds of similar quality yield less than 5.56%, the muni bond pays more after tax.

## Current Yields (March 2026)

**Municipal Bonds (AAA-rated, 10-year):** ~3.2-3.8%
**Investment-grade Corporate Bonds (A-rated, 10-year):** ~5.0-5.8%
**High-yield Corporate Bonds (BB-rated):** ~7.0-8.5%

## Break-Even Tax Rate

At what tax rate does the muni bond break even vs corporate?

If muni yields 3.5% and corporate yields 5.5%:
Break-even rate = 1 − (3.5% ÷ 5.5%) = **36.4%**

Only investors in 37%+ combined federal + state rate benefit from this muni bond over the corporate. Below 36%, take the corporate bond.

## Who Should Buy Muni Bonds?

✅ **High-bracket investors in high-tax states** (California, New York, New Jersey): Combined rates of 40-50% make munis very attractive.

✅ **Retirees in 32%+ bracket** drawing significant income from other sources.

❌ **Low-income investors (10-22% bracket):** After-tax corporate yield almost always higher than muni.

❌ **Tax-advantaged accounts (IRA/401k):** No benefit - muni interest already tax-free inside these accounts; the yield premium you give up is wasted.

