## Home Loan Prepayment vs Investment: The Indian Dilemma

You have ₹5 lakh. Should you prepay your home loan or invest it? This is one of the most common personal finance questions for Indian homeowners.

## The After-Tax Cost of Your Home Loan

Home loan interest at 8.5% sounds expensive. But tax benefits reduce the effective cost.

Under Section 24(b): Deduction up to ₹2 lakh/year on home loan interest for self-occupied property.

For someone with ₹30 lakh home loan at 8.5%, annual interest in year 3 ≈ ₹2.4 lakh:
- Deductible: ₹2 lakh
- Tax saved (at 30%): ₹60,000
- Effective interest cost: **₹1,80,000 on ₹2,40,000 = 7.5% effective**

Under 80C: Principal repayment up to ₹1.5L qualifies for Section 80C deduction.

## The Investment Side

Equity SIP at 12% CAGR: Well above the 7.5% effective home loan rate.

**₹5 lakh invested at 12% for 10 years: ₹15.5 lakh**
**₹5 lakh used to prepay 8.5% loan (saving effective 7.5%): Saves ₹11.2 lakh in total interest**

Mathematics favours investment over prepayment when effective loan rate < expected investment return.

## Psychological and Practical Factors

**Reasons to prepay:**
- Debt-free feeling has real psychological value
- Job uncertainty: Lower EMI provides cash flow cushion
- End of Section 24 benefit: After ₹2L interest/year, every extra rupee of interest is at full rate
- Approaching retirement: Better to be debt-free

**Reasons to invest:**
- Equity returns have historically beaten loan rates by 3-5%
- Tax on prepayment: None. Tax on investment gains: 10% LTCG
- Liquidity: Investments accessible; prepaid home loan equity is illiquid

## The Optimal Strategy

Split the difference: Prepay 50% and invest 50%.
Or: Ensure EMI is < 30% of monthly income, then invest all surplus.

