| Savings (20%) | ₹16,000 | Emergency fund ₹5K, SIP ₹10K, PPF ₹1K |

## Worked Example: $5,000/month Take-Home (USA)

| Category | Budget | Examples |
|----------|--------|---------|
| Needs (50%) | $2,500 | Rent $1,500, groceries $400, car $400, utilities $200 |
| Wants (30%) | $1,500 | Restaurants $500, subscriptions $100, entertainment $400, clothing $500 |
| Savings (20%) | $1,000 | 401k $500, emergency fund $300, Roth IRA $200 |

## Modifying the Rule for High Cost of Living

In Mumbai, London, or NYC, rent alone may consume 40-50% of income. Modify to 60/20/20 or 70/10/20 - but never reduce savings below 10%.

The power of the rule is not the exact percentages - it is the habit of intentional spending allocation.

## The Higher-Income Upgrade: 50/20/30

For those earning above median: flip wants and savings. Put 30% to savings and only 20% to wants. The difference compounds dramatically over decades.

At 20% savings rate: 43 years to financial independence.
At 30% savings rate: 30 years.
At 50% savings rate: 17 years.

