    content: `
## P/E Ratio: The Most Widely Used Valuation Metric

The Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio answers: "How much are investors paying for each rupee/dollar of company profit?"

P/E = Share Price ÷ Earnings Per Share (EPS)

If a stock trades at ₹1,000 and annual EPS is ₹50: P/E = 20. Investors pay ₹20 for every ₹1 of annual earnings.

## What Different P/E Ranges Mean

| P/E Range | Interpretation |
|----------|---------------|
| Below 10 | Deeply undervalued (or deep problems) |
| 10-15 | Undervalued, value investing territory |
| 15-20 | Fair value for mature companies |
| 20-30 | Growth premium priced in |
| 30-50 | High growth expected (tech, pharma) |
| Above 50 | Very speculative, risky |

**Nifty 50 historical average P/E:** 18-22
**S&P 500 historical average P/E:** 15-17 (trailing 12 months)

## Forward P/E vs Trailing P/E

**Trailing P/E:** Uses last 12 months of actual earnings - known data, more reliable
**Forward P/E:** Uses analyst estimates of next 12 months earnings - captures growth but depends on forecast accuracy

A company with trailing P/E of 40 but forward P/E of 20 is expected to double earnings in the next year - the high P/E may be justified.

## Shiller CAPE: Better for Market Timing

The Cyclically Adjusted P/E (Shiller CAPE) uses 10-year inflation-adjusted earnings to smooth business cycles. It is a better predictor of long-term market returns than standard P/E.

**S&P 500 Shiller CAPE March 2026:** ~34 (historically high)
**Historical average CAPE:** ~16-17
**Implication:** When CAPE is above 30, average subsequent 10-year returns have historically been lower (4-7% real) vs when CAPE is below 15 (8-12% real returns).

This does NOT mean the market will crash - just that future expected returns may be lower.

## P/E Limitations

- Works best for profitable companies; meaningless for loss-making companies
- Different industries have different "normal" P/Es - do not compare bank P/E (10-12) to tech P/E (30-50)
- Manipulated earnings distort P/E; prefer P/FCF (Price to Free Cash Flow) for deeper analysis

